description.text: This thing was made with Tinkercad. Edit it online https://www.tinkercad.com/things/3W5icp6QA4e

Just a simple spacer for the spools from http://supply3dpla.com , as they ship december 2011. I'm starting to run out of 608 bearings, so I tried to just use a 8mm hole in the middle and thread it directly onto the rod, and it works surprisingly well. Still, I have only used it for a week, so I don't know how it holds up in the long run. If you want a version with a bearing, check out this thing: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:14238

Print. Quickly put in while it's hot off the printer. The spool sides is pretty thin and weak, so don't apply too much pressure or it'll crack. Drill out the centre to 8mm to make it a good fit, we want to make sure the spool rotates around the centre so as not to risk the spacer wearing down and falling out. NB: As it rotates it slowly eats it way along the threads, so make sure to keep an eye on it. I use some tape around the smooth rod, and it keeps it pretty much in place so far. The very simple OpenSCAD file is included if you want to tweak it. It's just a quick hack though, and thus is not pretty at all.

title: High Precision (Hopefully!) switch for z probe

description.text:
Mechanical switch designed for high precision and repeatability.

My Z-probe was an inexpensive microswitch that I initially thought would be of sufficient repeatability to be useful. However, after trying three of them and failing to get repeatability within .2mm, I decided to try and build a better switch. A hard surface and single contact point seemed the way to go. I ended up with this design. I used (as you can see in the photos) nuts to tie the wires to the contact screws.

The bearings are small 6mmx2.5mm flanged bearings; I don't remember the designation - I bought them several months ago on eBay to make u-joints for my delta, and ended up going with Traxxas u-joints instead. They will press-fit in the lever, then an M3 nut will hold them together and allow them to move fairly precisely.

This probe is designed to clamp onto the effector of my delta; I attach it to run the grid probe sequence and endstop calibration routines.

The repeatability has been significantly better than my old microswitch, with the greatest variance I've seen being .020 mm, with normal variance being ~ .015mm. YMMV, of course.

I suspect if I were to replace the bottom contact screw with a copper rivet, and the top contact screw with a copper screw sharpened to a point, I could improve the overall performance even more, but this has proven sufficient for my needs. YMMV.

Let me know if you build it and how it worked for you! I can make the F3D files available if anyone wants them.

The zip file contains LARGE STL files generated by MeshMixer with supports that come off fairly cleanly and easily; they're the files I actually printed from.

Also, the top clamping screw goes through a 5mm m3 heat-set insert. I bought 100 on amazon for $8; they are lifesavers.

This is not a new thing. This is my version of http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:5103. I removed the pin in the shuttle and replaced it with a hole for the Pin/Rivet I designed. I made the arm holes larger to acomdate the rivets. The base is unchanged from the original and was a pleasure for me to both print, and test.

Print 1 base
Print 1 arm
Print 2 Shuttles
Print 2 pins. I printed 6 pins at once, this allowed for cooling of such a small shaft. It also gave me a reason to make more than one Do-Nothing. Clean up the base and shuttle with knife, file, sandpaper.
Place one shuttle in the base, and pin the arm to it with one of the rivets.
Place the second shuttle in the base, and pin the second arm home to the shuttle.

description.text:
I designed this to house the HS1177 Camera in the Ready Made RC Goby 210 frame. The camera angle is adjustable from 0-45 degrees (going below 25 degrees is unlikely if you stuffed components between the FC Stack and camera). The top plate slopes down at 10 degrees. Makes it nice for HD mounts, as you don't need the high angle mounts (generally heavier and awkward) to get the maximum angle on your HD Camera. The rear mount incorporates a notch for the antenna to be guided out the back. My VTX (TS5823) is mounted under the FC stack.

Assembly, the TPU prints will be flexible, and will require some pressure when screwing in the frame screws. You should use 8-9mm screws through the 4mm frame and 5mm screws MAX through the top plate.

I uploaded both file sets I have used, as some may want to print in ABS without post processing the holes. The files with TPU at the end have the walls thickened a bit to reduce flexing, and the mount holes reduced in size to help grip the M3 screws better. If you print in ABS I highly suggest using aluminum hardware, as aluminum threads into the ABS much better, and the threads will last, where steel hardware galls and pulls the threads with first removal.

description.text:
So I have only a few rolls of filament and wanted more colours. Searched and found a few thingis and even printed one of the designs.

All used marker pens to colourise the filament. Tried this and on my first attempt, while it did colour the filament, it was very "layery" and of course the felt tip got stuck in the hole and would not come out. Also the pens only inked a side and not very well. There was also colour bleeding because the pens left residue inside the plastic thingis.

I had some old inkjet ink lying about so decided to try it out. Of course only 4 colours CMY and Black.

Printed this thingi - http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:190118 - cut a piece of dense-ish sponge (dish scrubber), pumped a bit of blue ink in and snapped it onto my WHITE filament.

Note to self: Wear gloves next time.

Result was a light blue print as in the image.

Tried the same blue on Yellow filament and the result was a nice green for the fan blades.

That thingi colours the filament on all sides and gives a very even colour.

Must try some other mixes and see.

Everything leaves residue, even your filament. But as far as Inkjet ink is concerned, it is specifically made for being heated and passing thru a nozzle. That is how inkjet printers print. Does it leave residue in those printers. Yes. Can it be cleaned out. Yes.
Anyway compared to using a Sharpie to colour the filament, this method gives you more colours and less, if any, residue.

title: Bicycle Handlebar Mount/Bracket (Sized for Trek 7.3 Fx Bontrager Blendr Stem System)

description.text:
After I made stubs to fit the Bontrager Blendr mounting system on my Trek 7.3 FX bicycle, I started feeling bad that my husband's bike (Trek 8.3 DS) didn't have the nifty built-in system, so I built a mount for his bicycle to fit the stubs I had made (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1502511).

I can't guarantee this will fit the actual brand-name stubs, but it does fit the stubs I designed to fit the brand-name mount on my own bicycle, so I don't see why it wouldn't.

UPDATE 4/25/16:

I wasn't happy with my original design, so I've completely redone the connection between the bracket and collar to make it sturdier, using a GoPro-type 2-to-3 tab connecting system. It prints in 3 parts: the "collar" is the part that fits around the bike frame (sized for my husband's Trek 8.3 DS), and since I haven't learned to do the Customizer thing, you'll have to pull that into your favorite 3D modeling program to change it to whatever will fit your bike.

The bracket prints in two pieces, upper and lower, that are glued together using ABS glue. The assembled bracket mounts to the collar using an M3 bolt and nut.

The finished mount is much more solid than before. I'm planning to modify the bracket to print in one piece instead of two, but I haven't gotten around to it just yet.

I'm including the two variations of my stub design here, so you can download the whole system at once. They're also available separately at the URL listed above. Both have slots to accommodate a velcro strip. The curved one is meant for mounting a flashlight -- I like to coat the curved surface with the rubber stuff you can buy to dip tool handles in, for a better grip. The flat one can be ABS-glued to a phone case, or whatever else you want to print to attach to it.

A bullet pullet is an inertial device capable of removing a bullet from a brass case.

To build your own you will need a 3D printer, a 10 mm round stick and some glue to fix the stick in.

I wasn't able to make an insert that would "fit most sizes" so each caliber has its own shell holder.

To load a cartridge push it bottom first into the low end of the insert until you hear a click. Push it towards the same direction to remove it.

Twist clockwise to lock the insert in position.

ERRATA CORRIGE: The "top heavy" insert design was too fragile, at least in PLA. I've posted smaller, more robust inserts.

title: Printer base clamp and z-axis squaring mount

description.text:
These pieces are for a Geeetech aluminum prusa i3. The purpose is to secure the base of the printer to a platform, using the printer-to-base clamp part, and then make the z-axis perfectly square with this platform while reducing any wobbling of that axis by using the square mount for z axis part (x2).

Since the z-axis only contacts the y-bed/axis at two points on the very bottom it causes the z-axis to lean forward due to both of its motors to be hanging off of its vertical face. Also, once the x-axis is installed it causes an even greater lean.

For my platform I used three pieces of 20" x 20" x 1/4" MDF sheets, which i screwed together. Upon centering the printer on the platform I secured it using 4 x printer-to-base clamp (2 at either end of the y-axis). Then the two square mount for z-axis pieces could be fastened the the platform and printer.

title: Customizable magnetic Flashforge Creator Pro Leveling Indicator holder

description.text:
Use this to test the bed leveling of your Flashforge Creator Pro. It is also useful to test the flatness of your bed, for example, to detect bubbles after installing a PEI or BuildTak surface.

Features:

  • Magnetic
  • Customizable, easy to tweak dimensions to the tolerances of your printer.
  • Zero indicator insertion force. The indicator is held by two M3 screws rather than applying force fitting it in.
  • Uses proper metal threaded inserts.

I built it with these parts:

  • Neodymium Cylindrical (1/4 x 1/4) inches Cylinder Magnets. From ebay.
  • 2 M3x10 screws.
  • Dial indictor, from ebay. I prefer metric over imperial because of the higher sensitivity (1 turn per mm vs 1 turn per 0.1") and 3D is done in metric units anyway.
  • M3 thread heat inserts. McMaster http://www.mcmaster.com/#94180A333 . Insert with a hot iron, let the heat do the work, don't push it too hard. You can also buy similar threaded inserts from ebay but you will need to dremel one end to be conic as shown in the picture.
